Goodbye, schemas and SQL. Hello, JSON and MapReduce. CouchDB is a database built for the web.

CouchDB is a document-oriented database that can be queried and indexed in a MapReduce fashion. Incubated by Apache, it's the leading open-source software of its type. While achieving a breathtaking simplicity, it also offers a swathe of buzzwords, like incremental replication with bi-directional conflict detection and resolution.
CouchDB is deployed by the BBC, Meebo, Cloudant and Ubuntu One. It ships as a core feature of Ubuntu Linux. There are access libraries available in nearly every language.
“... makes Django look old-school in the same way that Django makes ASP look outdated.”

There are other databases out there, so why choose CouchDB? The tables of relational databases don't match well with object-oriented design (hence the need for ORMs), but CouchDB stores objects. Their strict schemas are a barrier to evolution, but CouchDB revels in it. Traditional databases specify their own APIs, but CouchDB uses good old HTTP.

Write offline-capable applications using a simple document model: CouchDB solves the data-island problem for you. Peer-based replication allows for flexible deployments, data-sharing between organizations, and no-hassle backups. Running CouchDB on the client with continuous replication to remote servers offers better latency and reliability than traditional three-tier architectures.

Committed updates are durable: CouchDB uses append-only storage, never touching any bytes already written to disk. Even truncating a CouchDB database file yields a consistent snapshot of an older version of the database. Writes are contiguous, giving CouchDB predictable performance even under heavily concurrent write load.

Start saving your data today, and adapt your queries as your application evolves, without migrating data formats. Query your data using familiar JavaScript (or your language of choice). CouchDB's views are optimized for real-time, rather than batch, workloads. Its MVCC data model is suitable for concurrent operations that require consistency.

CouchDB can scale from a smartphone to a data-center. Erlang and REST present the same, simple API whether running on a small local instance, an ad-hoc network of collaborators, or a multi-terabyte eventually-consistent cluster.
